    22	
    23	# @tevm/ethers
    24	
    25	A ethers.js utilities for Tevm
    26	
    27	### Try cloning our [minimal bun example on github](https://github.com/evmts/bun-starterkit)
    28	
    29	Don't worry if you aren't familiar with bun. It works with NODE/npm pnpm and yarn too
    30	
    31	## High level overview
    32	
    33	Previously the best way to get typesafe [contracts](https://docs.ethers.org/v6/api/contract/) with ethers was [typechain](https://github.com/dethcrypto/TypeChain) typechain improved the dev experience of using contracts via creating typesafe contracts via codegen. Tevm builds on this idea by providing the same benifit purely at runtime without any build or codegen steps.
    34	
    35	- `@tevm/ethers` exports a single function `createEthersContract`
    36	- `@tevm/ethers` only supports ethers v6 at this time
    37	
    38	## Installation
    39	
    40	To use `@tevm/ethers` simply set up tevm as normal and add the special `@tevm/ethers` package
    41	
    42	```
    43	npm install @tevm/ethers ethers@6
    44	```
    45	
    46	## API Reference
    47	
    48	### createEthersContract function
    49	
    50	**Type**
    51	```typescript
    52	function createEthersContract<TAddresses extends Record<number, Address>, TAbi extends Abi>(
    53	    contract: Pick<TevmContract<any, TAddresses, TAbi, any>, 'abi' | 'addresses'>,
    54	    options: CreateEthersContractOptions<keyof TAddresses & number>
    55	): TypesafeEthersContract<TAbi>
    56	```
    57	
    58	**Description**
    59	Creates a typesafe [ethers contract](https://docs.ethers.org/v6/api/contract/) from an tevm contract. This function provides typesafe contracts for Ethereum development with Ethers.js and Tevm.
    60	
    61	**Params**
    62	- `contract`: This parameter should be an Tevm contract. It should include the 'abi' and 'addresses' properties.
    63	- `options`: This parameter should be an object of type `CreateEthersContractOptions`. It should include either a `chainId` or an `address`, along with the `runner`, which should be an Ethers.js provider or signer.
    64	
    65	**Returns**
    66	The function returns a `TypesafeEthersContract`. This contract is a typed version of the ethers.js contract instance, which provides type safety and autocompletion for contract methods.
    67	
    68	**Example**
    69	```typescript
    70	// import a contract with tevm
    71	import {ERC20} from '@openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol'
    72	import {providers} from 'ethers'
    73	// create a provider or signer for the ethers contract
    74	const provider = new providers.JsonRpcProvider('http://localhost:8545')
    75	// create a typesafe contract
    76	const contract = createEthersContract(myContract, {chainId: 1, runner: provider})
    77	// enjoy typesafety and autocompletion in your ethers contract
    78	const balance = c.balanceOf('0x32307adfFE088e383AFAa721b06436aDaBA47DBE'),
    79	```
    80	
    81	## CreateEthersContractOptions Type
    82	
    83	**Type**
    84	```typescript
    85	type CreateEthersContractOptions<TChainIds extends number> =
    86	  | {
    87	      chainId: TChainIds;
    88	      runner: ContractRunner;
    89	  }
    90	  | {
    91	      address: Address;
    92	      runner: ContractRunner;
    93	  }
    94	```
    95	
    96	**Description**
    97	An options object type used by `createEthersContract` function. It can either provide a `chainId` if Tevm config has addresses for contracts configured for that chain or provide the `address` prop to specify the address directly. Both options require a `runner` property which is an Ethers.js provider or signer.
    98	
    99	**Params**
   100	- `chainId` or `address`: You should provide either the chainId or the address of the contract. If you use the `chainId` option, Tevm should have the addresses for contracts configured for that chain. If you use the `address` option, specify the address directly.
   101	- `runner`: This is an Ethers.js provider or signer.
   102	
   103	**Example**
   104	```typescript
   105	const optionsWithChainId = { chainId: 1, runner: provider }; // Using chainId
   106	const optionsWithAddress = { address: "0x1234...abcd", runner: provider }; // Using address
   107	```
   108	
   109	## See also
   110	
   111	[ethers v6 docs](https://docs.ethers.org/v6)
   112	
